Predictive Maintenance Classification on Machine Failure¶

Dataset from: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/shivamb/machine-predictive-maintenance-classification¶

Created by: Goh Chia Ching¶

Date Updated 17 Jan 2024¶

Introduction¶

This notebook aims to:

  1. explore predictive modelling on unbalanced datasets using different classification techniques
  2. create feasible and robust solutions for real world factory problems such as machinery maintenance

The dataset acquired uses synthetic data generated from the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository. More information on the dataset can be found here: ....

Now we've established a very simple summary of the data.

  1. The dataset is sufficient (10000 rows) for training
  2. The deviation between the records for Rotational Speed and Tool Wear is high, which means ....

We will now focus on estimating the Failure Type of the machine. In a more practical sense, models should first estimate whether a failure will occur or not then estimate the type of failure since a binary (yes/no) classification is faster and more accurate to predict in these situations. However for further complexity, we will be focusing on the Failure Type classification.

from scipy.stats import spearmanr

features = list(df.columns.values)
corrn = []

for index, feature in enumerate(features):
    corr, _ = spearmanr(df[feature], df['Failure Type'])
    corrn.append((feature, corr, index))
    
corrn.sort(key = lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)

for f, corr, i in corrn:
    print(i, f, corr)

Data Model Selection¶

Target variable: Here we want to predict the TYPE of failure (ie, if it will fail, and what type of failure would it be if it fails). Hence, we are dealing with a CATEGORICAL target. = Classification model

over fitting underfitting model update: k neighbours or generative

We will try

  1. Support Vector Machines
  2. Logistic Regression
  3. Decision Tree
  4. Random Forest
  5. Balanced Random Forest
  6. XGBoost (TBC)

1. SVC¶

In [15]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, cohen_kappa_score, accuracy_score
from sklearn.svm import SVC
In [ ]:
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
gammas = [0.001, 0.1, 1, 0.01, 10]
cs = [0.1, 1, 10, 100]
kernels = ["linear", "rbf"]
res = []

for kernel in kernels:
    for gamma in gammas:
        for c in cs:
            classifier = SVC(kernel=kernel, gamma=gamma, C=c) 
            
            # train the model
            classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)  
            
            # predict the credit score based on testing dataset
            y_pred = classifier.predict(X_test)  
            
            # get the accuracy value
            accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)  
            
            print("Accuracy:", accuracy, ", Kernel:", kernel, ", C:", c, ", Gamma:", gamma)
            res.append(accuracy)

print("\nHighest accuracy:", max(res))

In-Depth Testing¶

Deployment¶
